{
  "doc_id": "28258",
  "text": "Inadequate post-operative information has been observed in other settings. Henderson and Phillips [CITATION_1] reported that only 55% of patients routinely received discharge information, and the 45% had to ask for information if they wanted it. Information about their illness and recovery helps people cope better, enabling them to comply with the post-treatment constraints and to recognize and act appropriately should there be any complications [CITATION_2] . In addition, pre-operative knowledge reduces anxiety, pain, and stress, the need for physiotherapy and occupational therapy, and the length of hospital stay [CITATION_3] .",
